<collectionCode id="1580EFE4FFF9FFFAFB0C227FDEFDFC1A" LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" box="[1182,1267,884,910]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">USNM</collectionCode>
and 
<collectionCode id="1580EFE4FFF9FFFAFE9A2297DB46FC22" box="[264,328,924,950]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">UCR</collectionCode>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="732E7721FFF9FFFAFEAA22C8DED7FBBA" blockId="46.[264,1324,284,1470]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFF9FFFAFEAA22C8DBA5FC49" bold="true" box="[312,427,963,989]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Variation</emphasis>
. In both sexes, the hair on the ocellar tubercle varies from dark yellowish to brown, never black. The second antennal segment may or may not have black hair. In most of the males, there is a tuft of yellow hair at the apex of the venter of the gonocoxa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3B8B24AAFFF9FFFAFEAA2530DBB6FA8A" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="732E7721FFF9FFFAFEAA2530DBB6FA8A" blockId="46.[264,1324,284,1470]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFF9FFFAFEAA2530DBB2FBC1" bold="true" box="[312,444,1083,1109]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Discussion</emphasis>
. This species appears to be closest to 
<taxonomicName id="B4910CA2FFF9FFFAFC072537DE3DFBC1" box="[917,1075,1084,1109]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eriogonae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFF9FFFAFC072537DE3DFBC1" box="[917,1075,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">G. eriogonae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="5AD61648FFF9FFFAFBD72537DEADFBC2" box="[1093,1187,1084,1110]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The males may be separated by the absence of a small spur on the venter of the gonocoxa in 
<taxonomicName id="B4910CA2FFF9FFFAFB5B256FDB3EFB31" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="painteri" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFF9FFFAFB5B256FDB3EFB31" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">G. painteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="5AD61648FFF9FFFAFED22587DB95FB32" box="[320,411,1164,1190]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The vaginal furca in the female of 
<taxonomicName id="B4910CA2FFF9FFFAFCAB2587D9B4FB31" box="[825,954,1164,1189]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="painteri" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFF9FFFAFCAB2587D9B4FB31" box="[825,954,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">G. painteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="5AD61648FFF9FFFAFC5B2587DE2DFB32" box="[969,1059,1164,1190]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has a much more pronounced inward projecting ramus. These flies appear to be on the wing in southern Arizona in August, while other species occurring throughout the same range are found earlier in the year.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3B8B24AAFFF9FFFAFEAA2420D905FAD2" box="[312,779,1323,1350]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="732E7721FFF9FFFAFEAA2420D905FAD2" blockId="46.[264,1324,284,1470]" box="[312,779,1323,1350]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFF9FFFAFEAA2420DB9AFAD1" bold="true" box="[312,404,1323,1349]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Biology</emphasis>
. Immature stages are unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3B8B24AAFFF9FFFAFEAA2458DE3BFAFA" box="[312,1077,1363,1390]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="distribution">
